Investigation of CCHF in Iraq: 2022-2023
Crimean-Congo haemorrhagic fever (CCHF) is a severe viral disease that can be transmitted to humans through the bite of infected ticks or contact with the blood and tissue of infected animals. The disease is characterized by fever, muscle aches, headache and bleeding and has a high fatality rate, ranging from 10%â€“40%. In Iraq, CCHF is a significant public health concern. Cases have been reported sporadically since 1979 and there has been a steady increase in recent years due to factors that include climate change, changes in agricultural practices and increased human-animal interactions.
